---
import PageShell from '../../../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'overview', text: 'Overview', level: 2 },
  { id: 'why-panama', text: 'Why Retirees Choose Panama', level: 2 },
  { id: 'pensionado-visa', text: 'Pensionado Visa', level: 2 },
  { id: 'insurance-options', text: 'Insurance Options', level: 2 },
  { id: 'recommended-providers', text: 'Recommended Providers', level: 2 },
  { id: 'healthcare-system', text: 'Healthcare System', level: 2 },
  { id: 'costs', text: 'Cost Planning', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Panama Insurance Guide', href: '/countries/panama/insurance' },
  { title: 'Latin America Retirement', href: '/best/americans-retiring-latin-america' },
  { title: 'Costa Rica for Retirees', href: '/insurance-for/retirees/in/costa-rica' },
  { title: 'Pre-Existing Conditions', href: '/best/pre-existing-conditions-insurance' },
  { title: 'Mexico for Retirees', href: '/insurance-for/retirees/in/mexico' },
];

const providerColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'ageLimit', header: 'Max Entry Age' },
  { key: 'usVisits', header: 'US Coverage' },
  { key: 'panamaNetwork', header: 'Panama Network' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly (Age 60)' },
];

const providerRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', ageLimit: '74', usVisits: '180 days/year', panamaNetwork: 'Excellent', monthly: '$350-500' },
  { provider: 'IMG Global', ageLimit: '74', usVisits: 'Full US option', panamaNetwork: 'Good', monthly: '$300-450' },
  { provider: 'Aetna International', ageLimit: '64 (new)', usVisits: 'Included', panamaNetwork: 'Excellent', monthly: '$380-550' },
  { provider: 'GeoBlue', ageLimit: '84', usVisits: 'Blue Cross network', panamaNetwork: 'Good', monthly: '$320-480' },
];

const costColumns = [
  { key: 'item', header: 'Expense' },
  { key: 'monthly', header: 'Monthly' },
  { key: 'notes', header: 'Notes' },
];

const costRows = [
  { item: 'International Insurance (55-59)', monthly: '$280-400', notes: 'With US coverage' },
  { item: 'International Insurance (60-64)', monthly: '$350-500', notes: 'With US coverage' },
  { item: 'International Insurance (65-69)', monthly: '$450-700', notes: 'With US coverage' },
  { item: 'Local Private Insurance', monthly: '$200-400', notes: 'Panama-only coverage' },
  { item: 'Direct Pay (no insurance)', monthly: 'Variable', notes: 'Doctor visits $40-80' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Health Insurance for Retirees in Panama | Pensionado Visa Guide 2026"
  description="Complete guide to health insurance for Americans retiring in Panama. Pensionado visa benefits, insurance options, costs, and healthcare access in Panama City and beyond."
  headline="Health Insurance for Retirees in Panama"
  subheadline="Panama's Pensionado visa is legendary among retirees—major discounts on everything from healthcare to entertainment. Here's how to handle insurance in this dollar-economy haven."
  heroImage="/images/countries/panama-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Panama Quotes"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna"
>
  <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 mb-4">
    <strong>Affiliate disclosure:</strong> We may earn a commission when you click our links and purchase insurance. This doesn't affect our recommendations or the price you pay.
  </p>

  <h2 id="overview" class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Overview</h2>

  <p class="mb-4">
    Panama offers one of the world's best retirement programs: the Pensionado visa. Retirees get significant discounts on healthcare, transportation, entertainment, and more. Add in a dollar-based economy, modern healthcare in Panama City, and tropical climate, and you understand why Panama consistently ranks among top retirement destinations.
  </p>

  <p class="mb-4">
    Panama doesn't require health insurance for residency, but international coverage is strongly recommended—especially for retirees who want access to quality private care and the ability to return to the US for treatment when needed.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-8">
    <h3 class="font-bold text-lg mb-3">Key Facts for Retirees</h3>
    <ul class="space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Visa:</strong> Pensionado (requires $1,000/month pension income)</li>
      <li><strong>Insurance required:</strong> No, but strongly recommended</li>
      <li><strong>Currency:</strong> US Dollar (Balboa pegged 1:1)</li>
      <li><strong>Healthcare quality:</strong> Excellent in Panama City</li>
      <li><strong>Pensionado discounts:</strong> 25% off healthcare and much more</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h2 id="why-panama" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Why Retirees Choose Panama</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">The Pensionado Program</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Panama's Pensionado visa is legendary. Beyond residency, it provides: 25% off medical consultations and procedures, 15-25% off hospital stays, 10-20% off prescription medications, 25% off restaurant meals, 25% off airline tickets, 50% off entertainment, and more. These discounts apply for life and extend to your spouse.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Dollar Economy</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Panama uses the US dollar. No currency exchange, no conversion losses, no worrying about exchange rate fluctuations. Your Social Security and pension income arrives in dollars, and you spend in dollars. Simple.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Modern Healthcare</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Panama City has excellent private hospitals: Hospital Punta Pacífica (affiliated with Johns Hopkins), Hospital Nacional, Centro Médico Paitilla. Quality rivals US facilities. Many doctors trained in the US. Medical tourism is growing, which means facilities are accustomed to international patients.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Strategic Location</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Panama is a 2.5-hour flight from Miami, 5 hours from most US cities. The Canal Zone offers modern infrastructure. You get tropical living without being far from home.
  </p>

  <h2 id="pensionado-visa" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Pensionado Visa</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Requirements</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    The main requirement is proving pension income of at least $1,000/month. Social Security, government pensions, corporate pensions, and annuities all qualify. The income must be "for life"—IRA distributions and investment income typically don't count. Add $250/month for each dependent.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">No Age Requirement</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Unlike some retirement visas, Panama's Pensionado has no minimum age. If you have qualifying pension income—even from an early retirement at 50—you qualify. This makes Panama attractive for early retirees.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Application Process</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Process takes 3-6 months typically. You'll need: pension verification letter, police clearance, health certificate, passport copies, and photos. Many applicants use local immigration lawyers ($1,500-3,000) to navigate the process.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">No Insurance Required</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Panama doesn't require health insurance for the Pensionado visa. However, going without coverage is risky. Even with Pensionado discounts, serious illness or injury means significant out-of-pocket costs. International insurance provides security.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Applying for Pensionado?"
    description="Get coverage before you move. Compare international insurance options."
    buttonText="Get Pensionado Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="insurance-options" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Insurance Options</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">International Health Insurance</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Comprehensive coverage that works in Panama and the US. Best for retirees who: return to the US regularly, want access to US specialists, have pre-existing conditions, or want the security of comprehensive coverage. Cigna, IMG, and Aetna have strong Panama networks.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Local Private Insurance</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Panamanian insurers (ASSA, Pan-American Life, others) offer local coverage. Lower costs than international insurance. Age limits vary—some accept older applicants, some don't. Coverage limited to Panama. Good option if you won't need US care frequently.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Pensionado Discounts + Direct Pay</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Some retirees rely on Pensionado discounts and pay directly. Doctor visits $40-60 (minus 25% discount). Hospital procedures significantly less than US prices. Works if you're healthy, have savings for emergencies, and can return to US for major care.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Hybrid Approach</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Many retirees combine: high-deductible international insurance for major expenses and US coverage, plus direct pay with Pensionado discounts for routine care. This balances cost and security effectively.
  </p>

  <h2 id="recommended-providers" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Recommended Providers</h2>

  <ComparisonTable columns={providerColumns} rows={providerRows} />

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Cigna Global — Best Overall</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Excellent Panama network with direct billing at Hospital Punta Pacífica, Hospital Nacional, and other major facilities. US coverage up to 180 days/year for visits home. Pre-existing conditions covered with guaranteed acceptance option. Accepts applicants up to 74.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">IMG Global — Best Value</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Lower premiums than Cigna with solid Panama coverage. Full US coverage available. Pre-existing conditions evaluated case-by-case. Flexible plan options let you customize to your needs and budget.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Aetna International — Best for Panama City</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Strong relationships with Panama City's top hospitals. Premium service experience. US coverage included. Good choice for retirees settling in Panama City who want access to the best facilities.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">GeoBlue — Best US Network Access</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Blue Cross network access in the US—valuable for retirees who return often. Accepts applicants up to 84 (highest age limit). Good Panama coverage. Consider if maintaining US healthcare relationships is priority.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Need US Coverage Too?"
    description="Get insurance that works both in Panama and during your US visits."
    buttonText="Compare US-Panama Plans"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <h2 id="healthcare-system" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Healthcare System</h2>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Panama City Excellence</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Panama City has world-class private healthcare. Hospital Punta Pacífica (Johns Hopkins affiliated) is the flagship, with specialists in every field. Hospital Nacional and Centro Médico Paitilla are also excellent. Modern equipment, English-speaking staff, international standards.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Outside Panama City</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Healthcare quality drops significantly outside the capital. Coronado, Boquete, and other popular expat destinations have basic facilities for routine care, but serious conditions require Panama City. Plan accordingly if not living in or near the capital.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Pensionado Healthcare Discounts</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    With Pensionado status: 25% off medical consultations, 15-25% off hospital stays, 10-20% off prescriptions. These discounts apply at private facilities, not just public hospitals. Real savings that reduce the need for comprehensive insurance for some retirees.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Pharmacies</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    Pharmacies are well-stocked with medications at reasonable prices. Many drugs available without prescription that would require one in the US. Pensionado discount (10-20%) applies at most pharmacies. Brand-name and generic medications available.
  </p>

  <h2 id="costs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Cost Planning</h2>

  <ComparisonTable columns={costColumns} rows={costRows} />

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Total Healthcare Budget</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    For a 60-year-old American retiree with international coverage: $350-500/month insurance plus $50-100/month out-of-pocket totals roughly $400-600/month. Without US coverage: $250-350/month. With Pensionado discounts and direct pay only: $100-200/month average (highly variable).
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Cost-Saving Strategies</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <strong>High deductible:</strong> Choose $2,500-5,000 deductible and use Pensionado discounts for routine care. <strong>Exclude US:</strong> If you won't visit often or have Medicare, excluding US saves 30-40%. <strong>Panama-only local insurance:</strong> Lower cost than international; combine with US travel insurance for visits.
  </p>

  <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3">Pensionado Savings Example</h3>
  <p class="mb-6">
    A doctor visit costing $60 becomes $45 with Pensionado discount. A $10,000 procedure becomes $7,500-8,500. Over a year of typical retiree healthcare usage, Pensionado discounts save $1,000-3,000 annually. These savings partially offset insurance costs.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs" class="text-2xl font-bold mt-12 mb-4">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 mb-8">
    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Does Medicare work in Panama?</h3>
      <p>No. Medicare doesn't cover care outside the US. You need separate coverage for Panama. Many retirees keep Medicare Part A (free) for US visits. Whether to maintain Part B depends on how often you'll use US healthcare.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">How much pension income do I need for Pensionado?</h3>
      <p>$1,000/month minimum from a pension source (Social Security, government pension, corporate pension, or annuity). Add $250/month for each dependent. The income must be "for life"—IRA distributions typically don't qualify.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Is healthcare good outside Panama City?</h3>
      <p>Basic care is available in popular areas like Coronado and Boquete, but quality drops significantly. Serious conditions require Panama City. If living outside the capital, factor in travel time/cost for medical emergencies.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Can I get insurance with pre-existing conditions?</h3>
      <p>Yes. Cigna offers guaranteed acceptance with 24-month waiting period. IMG evaluates case-by-case. Local Panamanian insurers may have more restrictions. The Pensionado discounts apply to all care regardless of condition.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">Are the Pensionado discounts worth it?</h3>
      <p>Yes. 25% off healthcare, meals, entertainment, airfare, and more adds up significantly. Over a year, typical retirees save $3,000-8,000 across all categories. Healthcare savings alone often reach $1,000-3,000 annually.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="border-b pb-4">
      <h3 class="font-semibold mb-2">How long does Pensionado application take?</h3>
      <p>3-6 months typically. Using a local immigration lawyer ($1,500-3,000) speeds the process and avoids mistakes. You can enter on a tourist visa while the application processes, though some applicants apply from the US.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <CTABox
    title="Ready to Retire in Panama?"
    description="Get insurance that works in Panama and during US visits. Pensionado discounts plus international coverage = optimal strategy."
    buttonText="Get Your Panama Quotes"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna"
  />

  <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500 mt-12">
    This information is for educational purposes. Immigration rules, Pensionado benefits, and healthcare costs change. Verify current information before making decisions. Consider consulting with a Panama immigration attorney and insurance specialist. Last updated: April 2026.
  </p>
</PageShell>
